The differential cross section ratios after applying the background corrections are shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:crossSections} (left). There is an ${\ensuremath{x}\xspace}$-dependence to the ratios due to the neutron excesses in Fe and Pb. This manifests itself as an increased ratio in the valence quark region (${\ensuremath{x}\xspace} \geq 0.3$) where the intermediate vector boson is predominantly interacting with $d$ quarks. The ratios corrected for non-isoscalar effects are in the supplementary material. There is a weak preference for a smaller than predicted Pb/CH ratio at low ${\ensuremath{x}\xspace}$. These data are consistent with a previously published {MINERvA\xspace} inclusive analysis \cite{nukePRL}: a deficit relative to the simulation at low ${\ensuremath{x}\xspace}$ that increases as the size of the nucleus increases. The mean ${\ensuremath{x}\xspace}$ and $Q^{2}$ of data events in the lowest bin are approximately $0.07$ and $2.0$ {GeV$^{2}$\xspace}, respectively. The amount of shadowing observed in this bin contrasts with charged-lepton scattering fits, which predict a ratio of 1.03 for Pb to CH \cite{Bodek:2010km}.

The ratios of carbon, iron, and lead to scintillator agree well with the simulation in the largest ${\ensuremath{x}\xspace}$ bin, $0.4 \leq {\ensuremath{x}\xspace} < 0.75$. This bin corresponds to the region where the EMC effect is dominant. The current resolution of the data is not sufficient to measure the EMC effect between the different nuclei at the level observed in charged-lepton data \cite{slacRatios}. The data likewise imply the differences between the EMC effect in charged leptons and neutrinos must be smaller than the  current {MINERvA\xspace} data can resolve.

The ratios of total DIS cross sections as a function of $E_{\nu}$ for C, Fe and Pb to CH are shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:crossSections} (right). The ratio corrected for non-isoscalar effects is included in the supplementary material. A smaller-than-expected ratio in the higher-energy bins of the lead to CH cross-section ratio is observed. This is consistent with the deficit in the lower ${\ensuremath{x}\xspace}$ bins, as the higher energy neutrino events will tend to have a higher $E_{had}$ and a lower ${\ensuremath{x}\xspace}$. In contrast, the ratio of C to CH at low energy is larger than unity with a large uncertainty consistent with the MC ratio of about 1.1. This is observed in the ${\ensuremath{x}\xspace}$ ratios as well, where the data ratio is larger than the simulated ratios in all bins.

